text: Gundlach: "We have a major bear market under way in home builders. And there is no surprise there. I mean, we have had big increases in home prices, far in excess of average hourly earnings growth and income growth over the past 7, 8 years or so.

And we have interest rates that are up by 200 basis points on mortgages. And when I hear people on financial media say it doesn't matter because rates are still low, that's nonsense. It is the delta that matters when you've had 3% and lower 30-year mortgage rates for several

years in a row, obviously the pricing structure of the housing market has that factored into its construct. And now we have mortgage rates at 5.1%, possibly going to 5.5%. That would be almost a doubling of mortgage rates and we all know that mortgages as a monthly payment kind
of a game. So if the rate is higher, the -- no surprise that we see declines in home builder confidence and also the University of Michigan survey that says is this is a good time to buy a house."

@SullyCNBC The banker in Houston who Brian is interviewing on @cnbc is sooo wrong about the impact of a 5% mortgage rate (vs 3% a year ago). It is the delta (the rate of change) in the mortgage rate than is meaningful to the average buyer of a home He is market and tone deaf

I dont give advice but here are some observations: * In an investment world dominated by machines and algos be unimpassioned when trading and investing. * The aforementioned will provide a volatile and still uncertain backdrop for trading. * @cnbc Markets In Turmoil specials

as seen last night - is often a contrarian indicator. * The business media is reactive and not anticipatory. * As always, hide your portfolios and children from self confident talking heads - they are trying to sell you a service adn trying to sound smart. "They know nothing"

The correct move, thus far, was to - in an unemotional way - take advantage of this week's weakness by covering shorts and adding to longs. S&P futures +39 over fair value Nasdaq futures +145 DJ futures +340 There were multiple reasons for the drop over the last

six sessions - but few discussed possibly the most important one - ETFs and risk parity and other products/strategies that chase price momentum or allocate based on risk adjustments. Portfolio Insurance Part Deux was not discussed in biz media. It was on @realmoney
